00:22.000 --> 00:24.000
The Red-Headed League.

00:24.000 --> 00:28.000
The Red-Headed League.

00:44.000 --> 00:48.000
Scene 1. An interesting advertisement.

00:48.000 --> 00:50.000
The inside of Wilson's shop.

00:50.000 --> 00:56.000
It's a little shop with a lot of clocks, pictures, watches, etc.

00:56.000 --> 01:03.000
Wilson is writing at a table. Vincent Spalding is looking at the morning chronicle newspaper.

01:10.000 --> 01:14.000
This is interesting. What is? This advertisement.

01:14.000 --> 01:19.000
It is interesting for you, Mr. Wilson, because you have red hair.

01:19.000 --> 01:20.000
Go on.

01:20.000 --> 01:27.000
The Red-Headed League want to find someone new. Do you know about them? Listen.

01:27.000 --> 01:36.000
To all Red-Headed men, 21 years old or more, the Red-Headed League can now take a new man.

01:36.000 --> 01:41.000
We pay £4 a week to do easy work.

01:41.000 --> 01:47.000
Come to the league offices at seven popes court, Fleet Street, London.

01:47.000 --> 01:52.000
On Monday at eleven o'clock. You can get £200 a year.

01:52.000 --> 01:55.000
Really? Tell me about it.

01:55.000 --> 02:00.000
A rich American with red hair began the league.

02:00.000 --> 02:08.000
When he died, he gave a lot of his money to the Red-Headed League to give easy work to men with red hair.

02:08.000 --> 02:15.000
It's very good wages for only a little work. Why don't you go along to popes court?

02:15.000 --> 02:19.000
But millions of Red-Headed men walked out at millions.

02:19.000 --> 02:21.000
You need to live in London.

02:21.000 --> 02:22.000
But don't learn.

02:22.000 --> 02:30.000
You must have very red hair. You have very red hair, Mr. Wilson.

02:30.000 --> 02:32.000
Monday. Eleven o'clock.

02:32.000 --> 02:38.000
It's Monday today, and it's nearly eleven o'clock. Come on.

02:38.000 --> 02:50.000
Team two. Some easy work for Wilson. The office at popes court.

02:50.000 --> 03:00.000
A room with only a table and two chairs. Duncan Ross, a man with very red hair, is sitting behind the table.

03:00.000 --> 03:05.000
We can hear the noise of a lot of people out in the street.

03:06.000 --> 03:08.000
That?

03:11.000 --> 03:17.000
This is Mr. Jabez Wilson, and he wants to be in the league.

03:18.000 --> 03:23.000
And he has a good head of hair. I can't remember when I saw a better head.

03:23.000 --> 03:25.000
Ah! Stop it!

03:25.000 --> 03:34.000
I'm sorry, but we must be careful. Of course it is your hair. I can see that now. Please sit down.

03:35.000 --> 03:41.000
My name is Duncan Ross. Have you got a wife, Mr. Wilson? And children?

03:41.000 --> 03:45.000
No. I have no wife and no family.

03:45.000 --> 03:52.000
Oh, dear. Some of the men in our league have lots of red-headed children. We'd like that.

03:52.000 --> 03:54.000
I'm sorry.

03:54.000 --> 04:00.000
It's all right. You have that wonderful head of hair. When can you begin work here?

04:00.000 --> 04:09.000
It's not easy. I have a shop and I can stay in the shop, Mr. Wilson. What hours must I work?

04:09.000 --> 04:11.000
Ten o'clock to two o'clock.

04:11.000 --> 04:12.000
And the wages?

04:12.000 --> 04:13.000
Four pounds a week.

04:13.000 --> 04:14.000
What must I do?

04:14.000 --> 04:25.000
You must work here in the office all the time. That is very important. You cannot go out between the hours of ten o'clock and two o'clock.

04:25.000 --> 04:26.000
And the work?

04:26.000 --> 04:34.000
You must copy from this large book. And you must bring paper and a pen. Can you begin tomorrow?

04:34.000 --> 04:36.000
Yes, I can.

04:36.000 --> 04:40.000
Then goodbye, Mr. Java is Wilson.

04:47.000 --> 04:51.000
Scene three. Wilson tells his story.

04:52.000 --> 04:59.000
Sherlock Holmes' room. Holmes and Wilson are sitting in chairs. Holmes is smoking his pipe.

04:59.000 --> 05:04.000
Wilson has the morning chronicle in his hands.

05:04.000 --> 05:08.000
Most interesting, Mr. Wilson. Most interesting.

05:08.000 --> 05:11.000
Holmes? I'm sorry.

05:11.000 --> 05:13.000
Come in, my dear Watson.

05:13.000 --> 05:19.000
This is Mr. Java's Wilson. He is telling me a very strange story.

05:19.000 --> 05:26.000
This is Dr. Watson. He's a good friend. Give him the advertisement to read.

05:26.000 --> 05:29.000
He does a lot of writing, Watson. Do you see?

05:29.000 --> 05:33.000
Oh, how did you know that, Mr. Holmes?

05:33.000 --> 05:39.000
The right arm of your coat is different from the left. Your arm is on the table when you write.

05:39.000 --> 05:42.000
Yes, that's right.

05:42.000 --> 05:45.000
It's very strange, Holmes.

05:45.000 --> 05:47.000
It is strange, isn't it?

05:47.000 --> 05:50.000
Do you see the day and month of the newspaper?

05:50.000 --> 05:57.000
It's the morning chronicle of the 27th of April, 1890, two months ago.

05:57.000 --> 06:00.000
Now, Mr. Wilson, tell us about your shop.

06:00.000 --> 06:07.000
It's in Saxe-Coburg Square, Mr. Holmes. It's a little shop, and it doesn't make much money.

06:07.000 --> 06:09.000
Does somebody help you in the shop?

06:09.000 --> 06:12.000
Yes, a young man.

06:12.000 --> 06:16.000
Well, he's not very young, but he works for half wages.

06:16.000 --> 06:19.000
Does he? What's his name?

06:19.000 --> 06:27.000
Vincent Spalding. He's very good at his work. He likes to take photographs when he's not working.

06:27.000 --> 06:32.000
And he makes the pictures in my dark cellar, but he works well when he's in the shop.

06:32.000 --> 06:35.000
How did you first see the newspaper advertisement?

06:35.000 --> 06:39.000
Tell us that. Spalding saw it eight weeks ago,

06:39.000 --> 06:43.000
and we went to Pope's court and saw Mr. Duncan Ross.

06:43.000 --> 06:46.000
I told you about the visit a few minutes ago.

06:46.000 --> 06:50.000
Yes, yes. And I can tell what's in about it later. What happened next?

06:50.000 --> 06:54.000
Well, I was very pleased, Mr. Holmes.

06:54.000 --> 06:59.000
I went home feeling very happy, but that evening I began to think again.

06:59.000 --> 07:04.000
Copying from a book is strange work for a man to do, I thought.

07:04.000 --> 07:06.000
Very strange, yes.

07:06.000 --> 07:11.000
But the next morning I went to Pope's court with my pen and some paper.

07:11.000 --> 07:16.000
Mr. Ross was there, but he soon went away. Then I began my work.

07:16.000 --> 07:21.000
Well, I went in every morning at ten o'clock and went home at two.

07:21.000 --> 07:26.000
And on Saturday Ross was in the office again and gave me my four pounds.

07:26.000 --> 07:30.000
How long did you work there? Eight weeks.

07:30.000 --> 07:36.000
But today I went to the office at ten o'clock and the door was locked.

07:36.000 --> 07:39.000
This was on the door.

07:39.000 --> 07:45.000
The red-headed league is finished. June the 23rd, 1890.

07:45.000 --> 07:47.000
Then what did you do?

07:47.000 --> 07:51.000
I went to the office in the next building and I asked the man,

07:51.000 --> 07:54.000
what happened to the red-headed league?

07:54.000 --> 07:57.000
Who are they? He asked,

07:57.000 --> 08:00.000
who is the man at number seven? I asked.

08:00.000 --> 08:03.000
The man with the red hair, he said,

08:03.000 --> 08:06.000
his name is William Morris.

08:06.000 --> 08:09.000
He moved out yesterday.

08:09.000 --> 08:14.000
He has new offices at 17 King Edward Street.

08:14.000 --> 08:18.000
Well, I went to King Edward Street, Mr. Holmes.

08:18.000 --> 08:23.000
You did not find Mr. William Morris or Mr. Duncan Ross, am I right?

08:23.000 --> 08:25.000
You are?

08:25.000 --> 08:29.000
What did you do then? I went home to Saxe-Koburg Square.

08:29.000 --> 08:32.000
What does Spalding say about all this?

08:32.000 --> 08:36.000
He says, wait for a letter. You're going to hear something.

08:36.000 --> 08:40.000
What do you think? I need your help, I think.

08:40.000 --> 08:44.000
You are right, Mr. Wilson. I'm happy to help you.

08:44.000 --> 08:47.000
But first, I wanted to ask you one or two questions.

08:47.000 --> 08:51.000
Mr. Spalding was the first to see the advertisement, yes?

08:51.000 --> 08:54.000
Yes. When did he begin to work for you?

08:54.000 --> 08:58.000
About three months ago. How did he come?

08:58.000 --> 09:01.000
He answered an advertisement in the newspaper.

09:01.000 --> 09:04.000
Was he the only man to answer it? No.

09:04.000 --> 09:08.000
Twelve people answered it. Why did you take him?

09:08.000 --> 09:14.000
Because he was cheap. He is happy to work for half the usual wages.

09:14.000 --> 09:18.000
Yes. Tell me about him this Vincent Spalding.

09:18.000 --> 09:22.000
He's small and a good, quick worker.

09:22.000 --> 09:25.000
He's about thirty years old, I think.

09:25.000 --> 09:28.000
Where is he now? He's at the shop.

09:28.000 --> 09:31.000
That is all, Mr. Wilson. Today is Saturday.

09:31.000 --> 09:34.000
I'm going to have an answer for you before Monday.

09:34.000 --> 09:36.000
Thank you, Mr. Holmes.

09:41.000 --> 09:47.000
We must work quickly, Watson. Put on your hat. We are going to Saxe-Koburg Square.

09:48.000 --> 09:53.000
Scene four. Holmes meets Spalding.

09:53.000 --> 09:57.000
Outside the shop in Saxe-Koburg Square.

09:57.000 --> 10:00.000
Holmes is walking up and down.

10:00.000 --> 10:05.000
Now and then he hits the ground outside the shop with his walking stick.

10:05.000 --> 10:08.000
Then he hits the door of the shop.

10:08.000 --> 10:12.000
Spalding opens the shop door and looks out.

10:12.000 --> 10:15.000
The legs of his trousers are dirty.

10:16.000 --> 10:18.000
Can I help you?

10:18.000 --> 10:21.000
Yes. How can I get to the Strand?

10:21.000 --> 10:24.000
Third on the right and fourth on the left.

10:24.000 --> 10:27.000
He's a clever young man, Watson.

10:27.000 --> 10:31.000
He is? Why did you ask about that?

10:31.000 --> 10:34.000
He's a clever young man, Watson.

10:34.000 --> 10:38.000
He is? Why did you ask about that?

10:38.000 --> 10:41.000
He's a clever young man, Watson.

10:42.000 --> 10:47.000
He is? Why did you ask about the Strand? You know London very well.

10:47.000 --> 10:49.000
You wanted to see him.

10:49.000 --> 10:51.000
Not him. His trousers.

10:51.000 --> 10:55.000
His trousers? I don't understand.

10:55.000 --> 10:58.000
And why did you hit the ground with your stick?

10:58.000 --> 11:01.000
My dear doctor, this is not the time for talking.

11:01.000 --> 11:04.000
I must go and look at the roads behind Saxe-Koburg Square.

11:04.000 --> 11:06.000
Are you going to your work?

11:06.000 --> 11:09.000
Yes. I must go to the hospital.

11:09.000 --> 11:11.000
I must go to the hospital.

11:11.000 --> 11:13.000
I have things to do too.

11:13.000 --> 11:15.000
But I want your help tonight.

11:15.000 --> 11:17.000
Come at ten o'clock and Watson...

11:17.000 --> 11:19.000
Yes, Holmes.

11:19.000 --> 11:21.000
Bring your gum.

11:24.000 --> 11:26.000
Scene five.

11:26.000 --> 11:28.000
To catch a thief.

11:28.000 --> 11:31.000
Sherlock Holmes' room.

11:31.000 --> 11:36.000
Holmes, Jones and Maryweather are talking quietly.

11:36.000 --> 11:38.000
Watson comes in.

11:38.000 --> 11:41.000
Watson, you know Mr. Jones of Scotland Yard.

11:41.000 --> 11:45.000
And this is Mr. Maryweather. They're coming with us tonight.

11:45.000 --> 11:48.000
Hello, doctor. We meet again.

11:48.000 --> 11:51.000
I'm here because I want to catch John Clay.

11:51.000 --> 11:54.000
He's a killer and a thief.

11:54.000 --> 11:57.000
One of the worst men in London.

11:57.000 --> 12:01.000
It isn't going to be easy to catch him because he's very clever.

12:01.000 --> 12:05.000
It's after ten o'clock. We must go.

12:08.000 --> 12:10.000
Scene six.

12:10.000 --> 12:12.000
Watching and waiting.

12:12.000 --> 12:15.000
Inside the bank strongroom.

12:15.000 --> 12:18.000
There are boxes on the floor.

12:18.000 --> 12:20.000
It is dark.

12:20.000 --> 12:25.000
The door opens and Holmes comes in, carrying a light.

12:25.000 --> 12:29.000
Watson, Jones and Maryweather come after him.

12:29.000 --> 12:32.000
Holmes looks carefully at the floor.

12:32.000 --> 12:37.000
Maryweather sits on a box and hits the floor with his foot.

12:39.000 --> 12:41.000
How do you leave?

12:41.000 --> 12:50.000
No noise. Perhaps they can hear us.

12:50.000 --> 12:51.000
How long before?

12:51.000 --> 12:57.000
An hour. They're going to wait for Mr. Wilson to go to bed, then work quickly, I think.

12:57.000 --> 13:01.000
We're in the strongroom of the first bank. Did you know that?

13:01.000 --> 13:03.000
Mr. Maryweather works for the bank.

13:03.000 --> 13:07.000
Tell Watson, Mr. Maryweather, what do the thieves want?

13:07.000 --> 13:12.000
Our gold. It's in all these boxes.

13:12.000 --> 13:16.000
Lots and lots of it. Gold.

13:16.000 --> 13:20.000
We must wait in the dark. Get behind the boxes, everyone.

13:20.000 --> 13:23.000
Things are going to happen in the next hour, I think.

13:23.000 --> 13:28.000
When I hear or see anything strange, I'm going to come out quickly with a light.

13:28.000 --> 13:30.000
And then you must help me.

13:30.000 --> 13:33.000
Be ready with your god, Watson.

13:33.000 --> 13:36.000
Is everything ready upstairs, Mr. Jones?

13:36.000 --> 13:39.000
My men are waiting at the front door of the bank, Holmes.

13:39.000 --> 13:41.000
They can't get out there.

13:41.000 --> 13:46.000
Good. Now we must be quiet and wait.

13:46.000 --> 13:49.000
It's 1115, Holmes.

13:49.000 --> 13:51.000
Why?

13:58.000 --> 14:01.000
Now, have you got... what?

14:01.000 --> 14:03.000
You can't get away, John Clay.

14:03.000 --> 14:05.000
No, but my friend.

14:05.000 --> 14:08.000
There are three men waiting for him at the front door of the bank.

14:08.000 --> 14:13.000
You think of everything, Mr. Holmes. You're very clever.

14:13.000 --> 14:16.000
Your red-headed league was clever, too.

14:16.000 --> 14:20.000
But I am pleased to catch the famous John Clay.

14:24.000 --> 14:28.000
Scene seven. Holmes and Watson.

14:28.000 --> 14:30.000
Sherlock Holmes' room.

14:30.000 --> 14:33.000
Holmes and Watson are sitting in chairs.

14:33.000 --> 14:36.000
Holmes is smoking his pipe.

14:36.000 --> 14:41.000
They needed the red-headed league to get Mr. Wilson out of his shop.

14:41.000 --> 14:43.000
Do you understand that?

14:43.000 --> 14:45.000
Yes, I think.

14:45.000 --> 14:47.000
Um, yes.

14:47.000 --> 14:51.000
They wanted Wilson away from the shop for some hours every day.

14:51.000 --> 14:53.000
But how could they do it?

14:53.000 --> 14:59.000
Then Clay saw the colour of Ross' hair and thought of a red-headed league.

15:00.000 --> 15:03.000
When Wilson answered their newspaper advertisement,

15:03.000 --> 15:06.000
he went to work in their office every day.

15:06.000 --> 15:09.000
Then they had time to make their towel.

15:09.000 --> 15:11.000
Very clever.

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
So, Spalding is John Clay, the famous thief.

15:15.000 --> 15:18.000
When did you first know that?

15:18.000 --> 15:21.000
Spalding was happy to work for half wages.

15:21.000 --> 15:23.000
Why, I thought.

15:23.000 --> 15:25.000
Spalding often went down to the cellar.

15:25.000 --> 15:28.000
What's he doing down there, I thought?

15:28.000 --> 15:32.000
Suddenly, I thought about tunnels.

15:32.000 --> 15:35.000
Is Spalding making a tunnel, I thought?

15:35.000 --> 15:37.000
To another building?

15:37.000 --> 15:43.000
Watson, you saw me hitting the ground with my stick outside the shop.

15:43.000 --> 15:44.000
Yes.

15:44.000 --> 15:46.000
Now I understand.

15:46.000 --> 15:49.000
Was the cellar in front of the shop?

15:49.000 --> 15:51.000
You wanted to know that.

15:51.000 --> 15:52.000
Yes, I did.

15:52.000 --> 15:54.000
And it wasn't.

15:54.000 --> 15:57.000
The cellar was behind the shop.

15:57.000 --> 16:00.000
Then I saw the man Spalding.

16:00.000 --> 16:02.000
Did you see his trousers?

16:02.000 --> 16:05.000
Yes, I saw them.

16:05.000 --> 16:07.000
They were dirty, Watson.

16:07.000 --> 16:08.000
Why?

16:08.000 --> 16:11.000
Because making a tunnel is dirty work.

16:11.000 --> 16:13.000
Very clever homes.

16:13.000 --> 16:18.000
Then I went into the next street at the back of the shop.

16:18.000 --> 16:20.000
And what did I see?

16:20.000 --> 16:22.000
The first bank.

16:22.000 --> 16:24.000
The bank, yes, of course.

16:24.000 --> 16:27.000
Why is that young man making a tunnel, I thought?

16:27.000 --> 16:30.000
To get into the bank's strongroom.

16:30.000 --> 16:32.000
But why tonight?

16:32.000 --> 16:34.000
How did you know?

16:34.000 --> 16:38.000
Because they closed the offices of the red-headed league.

16:38.000 --> 16:40.000
The tunnel must be ready, I thought.

16:40.000 --> 16:42.000
And Saturday is a good day.

16:42.000 --> 16:45.000
The bank does not open on Sunday.

16:45.000 --> 16:48.000
Two days for the thieves to get away.

16:48.000 --> 16:49.000
Ha ha!

16:49.000 --> 16:52.000
But they didn't get away homes.

16:52.000 --> 16:54.000
You're very clever.

16:54.000 --> 16:56.000
That's very true, Watson.

17:04.000 --> 17:06.000
The three students.

17:23.000 --> 17:26.000
Scene one.

17:26.000 --> 17:30.000
Hilton Somes' story.

17:30.000 --> 17:34.000
Sherlock Holmes is sitting at a table, writing.

17:34.000 --> 17:36.000
It is evening.

17:36.000 --> 17:40.000
Watson comes in with Hilton Somes.

17:45.000 --> 17:47.000
What was at the door, Watson?

17:47.000 --> 17:50.000
This is Mr Hilton Somes Holmes.

17:51.000 --> 17:53.000
He teaches at St Luke's College.

17:53.000 --> 17:56.000
Can you give me some of your time, Mr Holmes?

17:56.000 --> 18:00.000
Today something happened at the college, and I was very worried.

18:00.000 --> 18:07.000
Then I thought the famous detective Sherlock Holmes is visiting our town.

18:07.000 --> 18:09.000
Perhaps he can help.

18:09.000 --> 18:12.000
I have a lot of work to do, Mr Somes.

18:12.000 --> 18:13.000
Perhaps the police.

18:13.000 --> 18:14.000
No, no.

18:14.000 --> 18:16.000
I can't go to the police.

18:16.000 --> 18:19.000
Well, tell me your story, Mr Somes.

18:20.000 --> 18:24.000
Tomorrow is the first day of an important examination,

18:24.000 --> 18:27.000
and I'm one of the examiners.

18:27.000 --> 18:32.000
Today, at three o'clock, the three exam papers arrived for me to read.

18:32.000 --> 18:38.000
Of course, every student would like to see these papers before they exam.

18:38.000 --> 18:39.000
Ha ha.

18:39.000 --> 18:40.000
Of course.

18:40.000 --> 18:42.000
We are always very careful with them.

18:42.000 --> 18:48.000
I began to read them, but at 4.30pm I went out to have tea

18:48.000 --> 18:50.000
in a friend's rooms.

18:50.000 --> 18:51.000
Where did you leave the papers?

18:51.000 --> 18:53.000
They were on my writing table.

18:53.000 --> 18:57.000
I locked my door and was away for an hour.

18:57.000 --> 19:01.000
When I arrived home, I saw a key in my door.

19:01.000 --> 19:05.000
Is it my key, I thought?

19:05.000 --> 19:08.000
No, that's in my pocket.

19:08.000 --> 19:11.000
Ah, it's Banister's key.

19:11.000 --> 19:13.000
Banister is my servant.

19:13.000 --> 19:16.000
Why did he go to your room this afternoon?

19:16.000 --> 19:19.000
He brings my tea in every afternoon.

19:19.000 --> 19:21.000
But you were at your friend's rooms.

19:21.000 --> 19:23.000
Did he forget that?

19:23.000 --> 19:26.000
Yes, and so his key was in my door.

19:26.000 --> 19:29.000
He is usually careful, but...

19:29.000 --> 19:31.000
Tell me about the examination papers.

19:31.000 --> 19:34.000
Where were they when you went back to your room?

19:34.000 --> 19:38.000
One was on a small table next to the window.

19:38.000 --> 19:43.000
One was on the floor, and one on my writing table.

19:43.000 --> 19:46.000
The first paper on the floor, the second in the window,

19:46.000 --> 19:49.000
and the third on the writing table.

19:49.000 --> 19:51.000
Yes, how did you know that?

19:51.000 --> 19:55.000
Please, tell us more of your very interesting story, Mr. Stone.

19:55.000 --> 20:00.000
First, I thought, did Banister look at the papers?

20:00.000 --> 20:05.000
So I asked him, but he said, no, I did not.

20:05.000 --> 20:08.000
And he is an honest man, Mr. Holmes.

20:08.000 --> 20:10.000
What happened next?

20:10.000 --> 20:15.000
Banister suddenly began to feel ill when I told him about the papers.

20:15.000 --> 20:19.000
He sat down on a chair, and I gave him a strong drink.

20:19.000 --> 20:23.000
Then I looked carefully at the table next to the window.

20:23.000 --> 20:25.000
What did you find?

20:25.000 --> 20:27.000
Small pieces of pencil.

20:27.000 --> 20:30.000
Did somebody break and sharpen a pencil?

20:30.000 --> 20:32.000
Yes, perhaps.

20:32.000 --> 20:34.000
Yes, that was it.

20:34.000 --> 20:36.000
Good. That helps.

20:36.000 --> 20:38.000
Two more things.

20:38.000 --> 20:43.000
I have a new writing table, but now there's a little cut on it.

20:43.000 --> 20:47.000
And there was a piece of black mud on the table.

20:47.000 --> 20:49.000
Is that all?

20:49.000 --> 20:50.000
Yes.

20:50.000 --> 20:53.000
Please help me, Mr. Holmes.

20:53.000 --> 20:56.000
It's an interesting story, Mr. Serms.

20:56.000 --> 21:02.000
Tell me, did any student visit you in your room after the papers arrived this afternoon?

21:02.000 --> 21:03.000
Yes.

21:03.000 --> 21:06.000
Daula Taras, a student from India.

21:06.000 --> 21:09.000
And the papers were on your writing table?

21:09.000 --> 21:11.000
Yes, but he couldn't read them.

21:11.000 --> 21:14.000
He was two or three meters away.

21:14.000 --> 21:16.000
But they were exam papers.

21:16.000 --> 21:18.000
Could he see that?

21:18.000 --> 21:19.000
Perhaps.

21:19.000 --> 21:22.000
The examination papers were in your room.

21:22.000 --> 21:24.000
Did anyone know that?

21:24.000 --> 21:26.000
Did Banister know that?

21:26.000 --> 21:28.000
No, nobody.

21:28.000 --> 21:30.000
Where is Banister now?

21:30.000 --> 21:36.000
When I ran out to find you, Mr. Holmes, he was on the chair in my room.

21:36.000 --> 21:38.000
He looked very ill.

21:38.000 --> 21:40.000
Did you leave your door open?

21:40.000 --> 21:41.000
Yes.

21:41.000 --> 21:44.000
But I locked the papers up first.

21:44.000 --> 21:45.000
Come then.

21:45.000 --> 21:47.000
We must go to your room.

21:53.000 --> 21:54.000
Scene two.

21:54.000 --> 21:57.000
Holmes visits the college.

21:58.000 --> 22:03.000
Serms, Holmes and Watson come into Serms' living room.

22:03.000 --> 22:07.000
Holmes walks to the window and looks out.

22:10.000 --> 22:13.000
That window does not open, Mr. Holmes.

22:13.000 --> 22:17.000
Nobody can enter the room through there.

22:17.000 --> 22:19.000
Your servant isn't here now.

22:19.000 --> 22:21.000
Perhaps he's feeling better.

22:21.000 --> 22:23.000
Which chair did you leave him on?

22:23.000 --> 22:25.000
The chair by the window.

22:26.000 --> 22:28.000
Near this little table.

22:28.000 --> 22:29.000
Yes.

22:29.000 --> 22:31.000
Yes, of course.

22:31.000 --> 22:33.000
The man comes in.

22:33.000 --> 22:38.000
He takes the three papers from the writing table to carry them across to the window.

22:38.000 --> 22:45.000
Because then he can see you when you come across the garden to the front door.

22:45.000 --> 22:50.000
But he didn't see me because I walked in through the back door.

22:50.000 --> 22:52.000
Ah, that helps.

22:52.000 --> 22:54.000
Can I see the three papers now?

22:55.000 --> 23:05.000
He carries this first paper across to the table near the window and begins to copy it.

23:05.000 --> 23:07.000
It takes him ten minutes?

23:07.000 --> 23:09.000
Fifteen, I think.

23:09.000 --> 23:10.000
All right.

23:10.000 --> 23:12.000
Fifteen.

23:12.000 --> 23:18.000
Then he puts it down on the floor, gets the next paper and begins to copy that.

23:18.000 --> 23:22.000
Then he hears you coming in the back door, Mr. Serms.

23:22.000 --> 23:24.000
He must be quick.

23:24.000 --> 23:29.000
He leaves the second paper on the table next to the window and runs.

23:29.000 --> 23:30.000
Where?

23:30.000 --> 23:32.000
Did you hear him running upstairs?

23:32.000 --> 23:35.000
No, I didn't.

23:35.000 --> 23:41.000
He's writing quickly because he breaks his pencil and needs to sharpen it again.

23:41.000 --> 23:42.000
This is interesting.

23:42.000 --> 23:45.000
The pencil was long and dark blue.

23:45.000 --> 23:47.000
Look at these pieces.

23:47.000 --> 23:50.000
And do you see the gold letters N-N?

23:51.000 --> 23:53.000
It's at the end of a word.

23:53.000 --> 23:56.000
Do you know Johann Faber pencils?

23:56.000 --> 23:57.000
I do, Holmes.

23:57.000 --> 24:02.000
I write for them.

24:02.000 --> 24:05.000
This is the piece of black mud.

24:05.000 --> 24:08.000
I can see the cut.

24:08.000 --> 24:09.000
What is that door?

24:09.000 --> 24:12.000
It opens into my bedroom.

24:12.000 --> 24:16.000
Did you go into your bedroom before you ran out to find me?

24:16.000 --> 24:17.000
No.

24:21.000 --> 24:24.000
A man can hide behind this curtain.

24:24.000 --> 24:26.000
What's this?

24:26.000 --> 24:28.000
It's a mud again.

24:28.000 --> 24:31.000
Your visitor was in this room, Mr. Serms.

24:31.000 --> 24:33.000
But why?

24:33.000 --> 24:35.000
Think for a minute.

24:35.000 --> 24:37.000
He hears you coming.

24:37.000 --> 24:38.000
What can he do?

24:38.000 --> 24:40.000
He must hide.

24:40.000 --> 24:44.000
So he runs into your bedroom and hides behind this curtain.

24:44.000 --> 24:45.000
Oh!

24:45.000 --> 24:47.000
Then he was in here.

24:47.000 --> 24:50.000
When Vanister and I were in the next room.

24:50.000 --> 24:51.000
Yes.

24:51.000 --> 24:53.000
That's right.

24:53.000 --> 24:57.000
Tell me, how many students live upstairs and go past your door?

24:57.000 --> 24:58.000
Three.

24:58.000 --> 25:00.000
All taking this examination.

25:00.000 --> 25:02.000
Who are they?

25:02.000 --> 25:05.000
There is Gilchrist.

25:05.000 --> 25:08.000
He plays football and likes running.

25:08.000 --> 25:11.000
His father was Sir Jabez Gilchrist.

25:11.000 --> 25:15.000
He was a rich man, but he gambled his money away.

25:15.000 --> 25:18.000
Young Gilchrist hasn't much money.

25:18.000 --> 25:20.000
But he works hard.

25:20.000 --> 25:22.000
And the Indian student?

25:22.000 --> 25:23.000
Yes.

25:23.000 --> 25:28.000
Dalat Ras is a quiet young man, but he works well.

25:28.000 --> 25:34.000
Then there is Miles McLaren, a very clever young man.

25:34.000 --> 25:39.000
But he doesn't study much, and he's worried about this examination.

25:39.000 --> 25:41.000
So he would like to see the papers first?

25:41.000 --> 25:45.000
Well, yes, perhaps.

25:45.000 --> 25:48.000
Can we speak to Vanister, your servant?

25:51.000 --> 25:53.000
Scene three.

25:53.000 --> 25:56.000
Some questions for Vanister.

25:56.000 --> 25:58.000
Insomes is living room.

25:58.000 --> 26:03.000
Homes, Watson, and soams are sitting in chairs.

26:03.000 --> 26:06.000
Homes is sitting at the writing table.

26:07.000 --> 26:10.000
Vanister is standing in front of him.

26:12.000 --> 26:15.000
Your key was in the door of this room today, Vanister.

26:15.000 --> 26:16.000
Is that right?

26:16.000 --> 26:18.000
Yes, sir.

26:18.000 --> 26:20.000
I don't usually leave it there, but...

26:20.000 --> 26:23.000
Tell me, when did you come into the room?

26:23.000 --> 26:26.000
About 4.30pm, sir.

26:26.000 --> 26:29.000
But Mr. saves his tea, but he wasn't here.

26:29.000 --> 26:32.000
Did you look at the papers on the table?

26:32.000 --> 26:33.000
No, sir.

26:33.000 --> 26:36.000
Why did you leave the key in the door?

26:36.000 --> 26:39.000
The tea things were in my hands.

26:39.000 --> 26:43.000
I thought, I can come back for the key.

26:43.000 --> 26:45.000
Did you forget to come back?

26:45.000 --> 26:46.000
Yes, sir.

26:46.000 --> 26:52.000
So the room was open all the time, and somebody in the room could get in or out?

26:52.000 --> 26:54.000
Yes, yes, sir.

26:54.000 --> 26:59.000
When Mr. Soams talked to you about the papers, you began to feel ill.

26:59.000 --> 27:02.000
So you sat down on the chair over there.

27:02.000 --> 27:05.000
Why did you go past the other chairs?

27:05.000 --> 27:08.000
I... I don't know, sir.

27:08.000 --> 27:11.000
Did you stay here when Mr. Soams ran out?

27:11.000 --> 27:14.000
Only for a minute or two.

27:14.000 --> 27:17.000
Then I locked the door and went to my room.

27:17.000 --> 27:21.000
Mr. Soams, I would like to visit the three young gentlemen.

27:21.000 --> 27:22.000
Is that all right?

27:22.000 --> 27:24.000
Yes, of course.

27:24.000 --> 27:27.000
These rooms are very old and very interesting.

27:27.000 --> 27:30.000
Visitors often go to look at them.

27:33.000 --> 27:35.000
Scene four.

27:35.000 --> 27:38.000
Gilchrist.

27:38.000 --> 27:44.000
Homes, Soams and Watson are outside the door of Gilchrist's room.

27:44.000 --> 27:47.000
They are looking at the doorway.

27:47.000 --> 27:51.000
Remember, gentlemen, you do not have a pencil with you.

27:51.000 --> 27:55.000
What are you... I owe it to you, Mr. Soams.

27:55.000 --> 27:59.000
Gilchrist, this is Mr. Holmes and his friend.

27:59.000 --> 28:02.000
They are looking at the building.

28:02.000 --> 28:04.000
Have you got a pencil, Watson?

28:04.000 --> 28:07.000
This is a most interesting doorway and I want to draw it.

28:07.000 --> 28:10.000
Oh, no. I'm sorry, Holmes.

28:10.000 --> 28:12.000
Have you, Mr. Gilchrist?

28:12.000 --> 28:14.000
A pencil? Oh, yes.

28:16.000 --> 28:18.000
There you are, Mr. Holmes.

28:18.000 --> 28:19.000
It is a beautiful building.

28:19.000 --> 28:21.000
Ah, thank you.

28:22.000 --> 28:25.000
Yes, Mr. Gilchrist.

28:25.000 --> 28:29.000
A beautiful building.

28:29.000 --> 28:32.000
Scene five.

28:32.000 --> 28:34.000
Dalit Rass.

28:34.000 --> 28:39.000
Homes, Watson and Soams are in Dalit Rass's room.

28:39.000 --> 28:43.000
The Indian is walking up and down the room.

28:43.000 --> 28:46.000
He looks worried.

28:46.000 --> 28:49.000
Homes is drawing on a piece of paper.

28:50.000 --> 28:53.000
A very interesting room, Soams.

28:53.000 --> 28:56.000
Thank you, Mr. Ross.

28:56.000 --> 29:00.000
Are you worried about something?

29:00.000 --> 29:03.000
Sorry. What did you say?

29:03.000 --> 29:05.000
Worried?

29:05.000 --> 29:08.000
Oh, yes. It's the examination.

29:08.000 --> 29:10.000
Is that all?

29:10.000 --> 29:12.000
Yes, of course.

29:12.000 --> 29:13.000
What?

29:13.000 --> 29:16.000
Good evening, Mr. Ross.

29:16.000 --> 29:18.000
Scene six.

29:18.000 --> 29:20.000
Miles McLaren.

29:20.000 --> 29:27.000
Homes, Watson and Soams are outside the door of Miles McLaren's room.

29:27.000 --> 29:30.000
Go away. I'm busy.

29:30.000 --> 29:33.000
I can't see anybody. Go away at once.

29:33.000 --> 29:35.000
McLaren.

29:35.000 --> 29:36.000
This is Mr.

29:36.000 --> 29:39.000
away. I'm busy. I can't see anybody.

29:39.000 --> 29:41.000
Go away at once.

29:41.000 --> 29:43.000
McLaren. This is Mr.

29:43.000 --> 29:46.000
away. It's the examination tomorrow.

29:46.000 --> 29:47.000
I must study.

29:47.000 --> 29:50.000
Come, my friends. It is not important.

29:50.000 --> 29:54.000
I'm sorry, Mr. Holmes, but is he a tall young man?

29:54.000 --> 29:56.000
Tall? No.

29:56.000 --> 29:58.000
McLaren isn't tall.

29:58.000 --> 30:01.000
Gilchrist is the tallest of the three.

30:01.000 --> 30:03.000
Good.

30:03.000 --> 30:06.000
And now, Mr. Soams, good night.

30:06.000 --> 30:07.000
What?

30:07.000 --> 30:09.000
Are you going?

30:09.000 --> 30:12.000
But tomorrow is the examination.

30:12.000 --> 30:14.000
What can I do?

30:14.000 --> 30:18.000
How are you going to take the pieces of pencil and the mud with me?

30:18.000 --> 30:23.000
Don't worry. I'm going to come back tomorrow morning with the answer.

30:26.000 --> 30:28.000
Scene seven.

30:28.000 --> 30:31.000
Homes is thinking.

30:31.000 --> 30:33.000
Homes is room.

30:33.000 --> 30:37.000
He and Watson are sitting in chairs.

30:37.000 --> 30:40.000
What do you think, Watson?

30:40.000 --> 30:42.000
Who began to copy the papers?

30:42.000 --> 30:45.000
McLaren. He said, go away.

30:45.000 --> 30:48.000
But did he want to hide something?

30:48.000 --> 30:54.000
Or perhaps the student from India, Mr. Ross, he looked very worried.

30:54.000 --> 30:57.000
Many people are worried before an examination, Watson.

30:57.000 --> 31:01.000
It is nothing. And the pencil was no help to us.

31:01.000 --> 31:04.000
What about Soams is servant?

31:04.000 --> 31:08.000
Manister. He's an honest man, Soams says.

31:08.000 --> 31:10.000
That's true, I think.

31:10.000 --> 31:14.000
Yeah. So why did an honest man...

31:14.000 --> 31:18.000
Oh, dear. I must think.

31:18.000 --> 31:21.000
Where's my pipe, Watson?

31:23.000 --> 31:25.000
Scene eight.

31:25.000 --> 31:29.000
All the answers to all the questions.

31:29.000 --> 31:31.000
Soams is room.

31:31.000 --> 31:34.000
It is morning.

31:34.000 --> 31:40.000
A very worried Soams is bringing homes and Watson into the room.

31:40.000 --> 31:45.000
Well, Mr. Holmes, can we have the examination later this morning?

31:45.000 --> 31:47.000
Or must I stop it?

31:47.000 --> 31:50.000
You can have the examination, Mr. Soams.

31:50.000 --> 31:52.000
But the young man isn't going to take it.

31:52.000 --> 31:53.000
You know him?

31:53.000 --> 31:57.000
Yes, I do. Please call Bannister.

31:59.000 --> 32:01.000
You have the answer, Holmes?

32:01.000 --> 32:03.000
Yes, my dear Watson. Look.

32:03.000 --> 32:07.000
Three. There were only two pieces of mud yesterday.

32:07.000 --> 32:10.000
Where did the third piece come from?

32:12.000 --> 32:16.000
Now, Bannister. I want the true story. What happened yesterday?

32:16.000 --> 32:19.000
I told you everything, sir.

32:19.000 --> 32:22.000
You have nothing more to say.

32:22.000 --> 32:24.000
Then I must tell you.

32:24.000 --> 32:28.000
When Mr. Soams called you into the room yesterday, you saw something on that chair,

32:28.000 --> 32:31.000
and you sat on it before Mr. Soams could see it.

32:31.000 --> 32:32.000
No, sir.

32:32.000 --> 32:38.000
Yes. And when Mr. Soams went out to find me, you opened the door and said,

32:38.000 --> 32:42.000
you can come out now to the man hiding behind the curtain.

32:42.000 --> 32:44.000
There was no man, sir.

32:44.000 --> 32:46.000
That isn't true.

32:46.000 --> 32:50.000
But please go and stand next to the bedroom door.

32:50.000 --> 32:54.000
Soams, please go and ask young Gilchrist to come down.

33:01.000 --> 33:06.000
Mr. Gilchrist, there are only the five of us to hear your answer to my question.

33:06.000 --> 33:09.000
Why did you copy the examination papers yesterday?

33:09.000 --> 33:13.000
No, Mr. Gilchrist, sir. I never said anything.

33:13.000 --> 33:16.000
No. But you are helping us now, Bannister.

33:16.000 --> 33:18.000
Tell us, Mr. Gilchrist.

33:22.000 --> 33:25.000
You did something very wrong, Gilchrist.

33:25.000 --> 33:28.000
But you're sorry now. I can see that.

33:28.000 --> 33:31.000
I'm going to tell you the story, Soams.

33:31.000 --> 33:34.000
Mr. Gilchrist first saw the papers through the window.

33:34.000 --> 33:37.000
But nobody can get in through the window.

33:37.000 --> 33:42.000
That's true. But a very tall man can look through it from the garden.

33:43.000 --> 33:48.000
I could not understand this cut, but then I remembered.

33:48.000 --> 33:50.000
Gilchrist likes running.

33:50.000 --> 33:53.000
But how does that help, Holmes?

33:53.000 --> 33:55.000
Think, Watson.

33:55.000 --> 33:58.000
This young man went running yesterday afternoon.

33:58.000 --> 34:02.000
When he walked home, his running shoes were in his hands.

34:02.000 --> 34:06.000
And running shoes have spikes, of course.

34:06.000 --> 34:09.000
Yes, Gilchrist went past this window and looked in.

34:09.000 --> 34:12.000
He's a tall young man, you see.

34:12.000 --> 34:15.000
He saw the exam papers on the writing table.

34:15.000 --> 34:19.000
Then he went past Soams's door and saw the key in it.

34:19.000 --> 34:23.000
And he went into the room and put his shoes on the writing table.

34:23.000 --> 34:25.000
And a spike cut into it.

34:25.000 --> 34:26.000
Yes, Watson.

34:26.000 --> 34:30.000
What did you put on that chair near the window?

34:30.000 --> 34:31.000
My watch.

34:31.000 --> 34:36.000
He puts his watch on the chair, then begins to copy one of the papers.

34:36.000 --> 34:41.000
I'm going to see Mr. Soams when he comes back across the garden, he thinks.

34:41.000 --> 34:44.000
But you walk in through the back door, Soams.

34:44.000 --> 34:46.000
Then what?

34:46.000 --> 34:48.000
Gilchrist hears you coming.

34:48.000 --> 34:53.000
Quickly takes his running shoes and runs into your bedroom to hide.

34:53.000 --> 34:57.000
One shoe leaves some black mud behind the curtain.

34:57.000 --> 34:59.000
Is this all true, Mr. Gilchrist?

34:59.000 --> 35:03.000
I found the same black mud on your shoes.

35:03.000 --> 35:05.000
Yes, sir. It's true.

35:05.000 --> 35:08.000
Have you nothing more to say?

35:09.000 --> 35:12.000
I have a letter here, Mr. Soams.

35:12.000 --> 35:17.000
Early this morning I began to write to you.

35:17.000 --> 35:22.000
It says, I'm not going to take the examination.

35:22.000 --> 35:25.000
I'm going to South Africa to work for the police there.

35:25.000 --> 35:27.000
I see.

35:27.000 --> 35:30.000
You're not going to take the examination now.

35:30.000 --> 35:32.000
I'm pleased to hear that.

35:32.000 --> 35:34.000
Mr. Bennister talked to me.

35:34.000 --> 35:37.000
This is the right thing to do.

35:37.000 --> 35:39.000
I understand that now.

35:39.000 --> 35:44.000
Gilchrist was in the bedroom, Bennister, and you didn't tell Mr. Soams.

35:44.000 --> 35:48.000
When you saw Gilchrist's watch, you sat on it to hide it.

35:48.000 --> 35:49.000
Why?

35:49.000 --> 35:56.000
Well, sir, I was once assigned to Sir Jabez, Gilchrist, this young gentleman's father.

35:56.000 --> 36:03.000
Ah! When he gambled his money away, I moved to the college to be a servant.

36:03.000 --> 36:06.000
But I always remembered Sir Jabez.

36:06.000 --> 36:08.000
He was good to me.

36:08.000 --> 36:11.000
So I did everything to help his son here.

36:11.000 --> 36:19.000
And yesterday, when Mr. Soams called me yesterday, I saw Mr. Gilchrist's watch on the chair.

36:19.000 --> 36:23.000
He looked at the examination papers, I thought.

36:23.000 --> 36:27.000
And I quickly sat down on the watch before Mr. Soams saw it.

36:27.000 --> 36:30.000
Then Mr. Soams visited me.

36:30.000 --> 36:34.000
Yes, sir. And I called young Mr. Gilchrist.

36:34.000 --> 36:38.000
You looked at the exam papers, I said to him.

36:38.000 --> 36:40.000
Did you copy them?

36:40.000 --> 36:43.000
Yes, he said. I did.

36:43.000 --> 36:47.000
Then you cannot take the exam, I said.

36:47.000 --> 36:49.000
Think of your father.

36:49.000 --> 36:54.000
He was an honest man, and you must be honest too.

36:54.000 --> 36:57.000
I wanted to stop him, Mr. Holmes.

36:57.000 --> 36:59.000
You were right, Bennister.

36:59.000 --> 37:02.000
Well, Soams, you have your answers now.

37:02.000 --> 37:06.000
And you young man did wrong. But you're going to put things right.

37:06.000 --> 37:09.000
You can thank Bennister for that.

37:09.000 --> 37:11.000
I do thank him, sir.

37:11.000 --> 37:14.000
Come, Watson. Our work is finished here.

37:14.000 --> 37:16.000
Yes, Holmes.

